It's important to remember
the original technology,

00:43.502 --> 00:45.294
<i> learning with our hands,</i>

00:45.337 --> 00:49.214
and passing on a craft is
kind of a responsibility.

00:49.258 --> 00:50.799
<i> - My name is</i>
<i> Michael Hoops.</i>

00:50.843 --> 00:54.053
I've been bladesmithing
for about seven years.

00:54.096 --> 00:57.222
<i> I'm a big consumer</i>
<i> of "Dungeons and Dragons."</i>

00:57.266 --> 00:59.641
<i> I think that is probably</i>
<i> one of the big reasons</i>

00:59.685 --> 01:01.643
that I went
into bladesmithing.

01:01.687 --> 01:04.521
<i> - My name's Andy Alm.</i>
<i> I'm 27 years old.</i>

01:04.565 --> 01:07.107
<i> I've been bladesmithing</i>
<i> for about 12 years.</i>

01:07.151 --> 01:09.610
<i> As well as bladesmithing,</i>
<i> I worked in radio</i>

01:09.653 --> 01:13.072
<i> for about seven years</i>
<i> as a news broadcaster.</i>

01:13.115 --> 01:15.866
Weather on the eights,
guaranteed.

01:15.910 --> 01:17.868
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

01:17.912 --> 01:19.870
<i> - My name is Shayne Carter,</i>
<i> I'm 55 years old.</i>

01:19.914 --> 01:22.956
I started shoeing horses
at the age of 13 with my father.

01:23.000 --> 01:25.167
<i> Once you learn how to forge</i>
<i> a piece of iron,</i>

01:25.211 --> 01:27.711
it's endless where
that journey will take you.

01:27.755 --> 01:31.090
- Good morning, bladesmiths,
and welcome to the Forge.

01:31.133 --> 01:33.467
You're here to engage
in three rounds of competition

01:33.511 --> 01:35.928
specifically designed to test
every aspect

01:35.971 --> 01:38.472
of your edged weapon-making
capabilities,

01:38.516 --> 01:41.558
from design to forge
to fit and finish.

01:41.602 --> 01:43.894
At the end of each round
you'll be presenting your work

01:43.938 --> 01:45.896
to our panel
of expert judges.

01:45.940 --> 01:48.440
First up, joining
our "Forged in Fire" family

01:48.484 --> 01:50.067
for the first time

01:50.111 --> 01:51.944
while J. Neilson recovers
from hand surgery

01:51.987 --> 01:55.114
is a man known the world over
for his exceptional blades--

01:55.157 --> 01:57.241
Mastersmith Jason Knight.

01:57.284 --> 01:59.618
Next, historic weapons
re-creations specialist

01:59.662 --> 02:01.411
David Baker,

02:01.455 --> 02:04.331
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

02:04.375 --> 02:07.084
They decide which of you will be
the "Forged in Fire" champion

02:07.128 --> 02:10.087
and leaves here
with a check for $10,000.

02:10.131 --> 02:13.006
Today's challenge,
you'll be working with these.

02:14.760 --> 02:17.553
Brand-new tools.

02:17.596 --> 02:18.887
What do you think,
Shane?

02:18.931 --> 02:20.973
- It's looking
a little rough there.

02:21.016 --> 02:22.391
- Right, it's not rough enough,
'cause this is "Forged in Fire."

02:27.314 --> 02:29.106
- Now we're talking.

02:29.150 --> 02:30.941
- What the hell am I
supposed to do with this?

02:30.985 --> 02:32.401
- Your first challenge
is to take

02:32.444 --> 02:34.570
at least one
of these old materials

02:34.613 --> 02:37.030
and combine it
with one of these new tools,

02:37.074 --> 02:40.242
and to forge a blade
in your signature style.

02:40.286 --> 02:41.910
Keep in mind
that in the second round

02:41.954 --> 02:43.453
you'll be putting handles
on your blades,

02:43.497 --> 02:45.914
turning them
into fully functional weapons

02:45.958 --> 02:48.041
that will then be tested
for strength and durability

02:48.085 --> 02:50.085
in a bone marrow chop,

02:50.129 --> 02:53.046
and for sharpness
in a sandbag slice.

02:53.090 --> 02:56.300
The blades themselves must fall
within the following parameters.

02:56.343 --> 02:58.093
<i>The length of the blade,</i>
<i>not including the tang,</i>

02:58.137 --> 03:00.929
<i> must be between 10</i>
<i> and 12 inches.</i>

03:00.973 --> 03:02.264
<i> The overall length</i>
<i> of your weapon</i>

03:02.308 --> 03:04.808
<i> must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

03:04.852 --> 03:06.643
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

03:06.687 --> 03:08.520
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:08.564 --> 03:11.732
Your ten minute design window
starts now.

03:11.775 --> 03:15.360
<i> [rock music]</i>

03:15.404 --> 03:16.862
- Many bad things.

03:16.906 --> 03:19.031
<i> I'm gonna grab</i>
<i> a canister.</i>

03:19.074 --> 03:22.034
It's gonna be
on the outside of the blade.

03:22.077 --> 03:24.286
<i> The inside is gonna be</i>
<i> all band saw blades.</i>

03:24.330 --> 03:25.954
All right,
where's my paper?

03:25.998 --> 03:27.873
<i> I'm designing</i>
<i> a camp knife.</i>

03:27.917 --> 03:30.292
<i> I need to make a knife</i>
<i> to perform.</i>

03:30.336 --> 03:32.920
It has to look good,
but it's more important

03:32.963 --> 03:35.130
<i> that it performs well.</i>

03:35.174 --> 03:37.883
<i> - For my blade, I've decided</i>
<i> to use a crowbar, a chisel,</i>

03:37.927 --> 03:39.509
and some old band saw blades.

03:39.553 --> 03:41.261
<i> I'm gonna make a kopis.</i>

03:41.305 --> 03:43.263
<i> This is</i>
<i> an ancient Greek weapon.</i>

03:43.307 --> 03:46.350
<i>It's got a big belly that leans</i>
<i> forward into the cut.</i>

03:46.393 --> 03:48.143
<i> That's the main part</i>

03:48.187 --> 03:49.686
<i> that's gonna be doing</i>
<i> all the chopping,</i>

03:49.730 --> 03:51.438
<i> and that should leave</i>
<i> plenty of tip</i>

03:51.482 --> 03:53.690
in order to stay sharp enough
for the slicing test.

03:53.734 --> 03:56.026
- I'm watching these guys,
and he's got a lot of--

03:56.070 --> 03:58.028
I don't know what all he's--
he's got a crowbar.

03:58.072 --> 03:59.446
I don't know if he wants
to break into a place

03:59.490 --> 04:00.405
or make a knife
out of it.

04:00.449 --> 04:02.449
[both laughing]

04:02.493 --> 04:05.494
I'm gonna take the crowbar,
which is new steel,

04:05.537 --> 04:06.745
and I'm gonna take
the coiled springs,

04:06.789 --> 04:08.538
which is old steel.

04:08.582 --> 04:11.375
<i>So I've chosen a recurve design</i>
<i> for the fact</i>

04:11.418 --> 04:15.504
<i> that it's a great chopper</i>
<i> and it slices well.</i>

04:15.547 --> 04:18.548
<i> - I'm designing</i>
<i> a camp style knife.</i>

04:18.592 --> 04:21.677
I'm going for the axe

04:21.720 --> 04:25.180
<i> and a couple</i>
<i> of broken band saw blades.</i>

04:25.224 --> 04:27.975
- Your ten minute design window
is now closed.

04:28.018 --> 04:31.853
Your three hour forging time
starts...

04:31.897 --> 04:33.272
now.

04:33.315 --> 04:35.190
- And here we go.

04:35.234 --> 04:36.984
<i> [rock music]</i>

04:37.027 --> 04:38.735
- Harry's the only guy
that's throwing steel

04:38.779 --> 04:40.445
into the fire right away.
- That's a good idea.

04:42.074 --> 04:43.573
- If you're gonna use
that crowbar,

04:43.617 --> 04:45.409
you're gonna have to turn it
into bar stock.

04:45.452 --> 04:48.745
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

04:48.789 --> 04:51.039
- Shayne went over and
spark-tested that metal.

04:51.083 --> 04:54.084
- That's a good idea.
The more complex the spark,

04:54.128 --> 04:57.087
the more likely you have
a high carbon steel.

04:57.131 --> 04:59.840
<i> - My biggest weakness is</i>
<i> is I'm color-blind,</i>

04:59.883 --> 05:01.717
<i> so a lot of times</i>
<i> I have</i>

05:01.760 --> 05:03.051
<i> a little bit of trouble</i>
<i> with the heat treat,</i>

05:03.095 --> 05:05.387
but after 42 years
of being a farrier,

05:05.431 --> 05:07.514
<i> my biggest strength</i>
<i> is experience</i>

05:07.558 --> 05:09.683
<i> and the ability</i>
<i> to forge.</i>

05:09.727 --> 05:11.643
- Shayne is
like a machine.

05:11.687 --> 05:14.187
<i> - I'm able to look</i>
<i> through that piece of steel</i>

05:14.231 --> 05:16.148
<i> and see</i>
<i> a finished project.</i>

05:16.191 --> 05:18.483
- Look at this guy go to town
over here.

05:18.527 --> 05:20.610
Who needs a power hammer?
I got a Shayne.

05:20.654 --> 05:22.029
[laughter]

05:22.072 --> 05:23.822
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

05:23.866 --> 05:26.158
- Mike has just pulled out
that entire axe head.

05:26.201 --> 05:29.077
- Clean out the inside,
switch something in there,

05:29.121 --> 05:31.747
weld that all up, and you got
a nice chunk of metal.

05:31.790 --> 05:35.542
- I haven't done
this big of a forge-weld

05:35.586 --> 05:37.586
<i> of two different materials.</i>

05:37.629 --> 05:39.463
<i> I'm worried a little bit</i>
<i> about the time,</i>

05:39.506 --> 05:41.423
just because of prepping
all the material,

05:41.467 --> 05:44.217
but if this weld goes good,
I should be clean

05:44.261 --> 05:46.428
to just hit the hammer
and sail on.

05:46.472 --> 05:48.555
When my fiancée proposed to me,
I told her

05:48.599 --> 05:51.475
that we couldn't get married
until I made a suit of armor.

05:51.518 --> 05:54.269
<i> If I win the $10,000,</i>
<i> I would make</i>

05:54.313 --> 05:57.189
an actual full
medieval plate mail--

05:57.232 --> 06:00.484
the helm, the pauldrons,
the whole shebang.

06:00.527 --> 06:04.404
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

06:04.448 --> 06:08.116
- Chisel,
crowbar--crowbar.

06:08.160 --> 06:10.786
The most important part
about using recycled materials

06:10.829 --> 06:12.829
is to get
that forge weld,

06:12.873 --> 06:15.540
<i> so I'm most nervous</i>
<i> about that crowbar.</i>

06:15.584 --> 06:18.168
I have no idea
what that is made out of.

06:18.212 --> 06:19.753
- We have a prepped billet.

06:19.797 --> 06:21.546
- Heading for the fire.
- All right.

06:21.590 --> 06:23.131
<i>- When you're working in metal,</i>
<i> you're working</i>

06:23.175 --> 06:25.842
<i> in this time-honored,</i>
<i> timeless material.</i>

06:25.886 --> 06:27.177
<i> Making something</i>
<i> for somebody else</i>

06:27.221 --> 06:29.179
is really irrelevant.

06:29.223 --> 06:31.056
You're making it for yourself.
You're extending yourself.

06:31.100 --> 06:32.599
- Having fun yet?

06:32.643 --> 06:34.309
- You know,
as soon as you get here,

06:34.353 --> 06:35.143
all of a sudden you realize
you're in a hurry.

06:35.187 --> 06:37.104
- Welding.

06:37.147 --> 06:39.731
- It looks like Andy might be
doing a canister Damascus.

06:39.775 --> 06:42.818
- One canister might not be
enough for a knife of this size,

06:42.861 --> 06:46.321
so I'm grabbing two and
I'm gonna weld them together.

06:46.365 --> 06:49.116
- The problem with have a weld
in the middle of your canister

06:49.159 --> 06:51.576
is when you start
to squeeze that,

06:51.620 --> 06:53.954
<i> the first thing that pops</i>
<i> is a weld.</i>

06:53.997 --> 06:56.248
- I try to put all my stuff
inside the canister

06:56.291 --> 06:59.042
and weld it up
with some powdered steel.

06:59.086 --> 07:02.295
That's gonna be badass.
Now I just need to find

07:02.339 --> 07:03.964
a little bit
of something flammable

07:04.007 --> 07:06.007
so I can do
dangerous things.

07:06.051 --> 07:08.427
I'm putting some of this WD-40
in this canister,

07:08.470 --> 07:10.095
and that's gonna
hopefully burn out

07:10.139 --> 07:13.014
<i> any of the excess oxygen</i>
<i> before I weld it.</i>

07:13.058 --> 07:14.433
The downside to this is

07:14.476 --> 07:16.768
I'm basically making
a pipe bomb.

07:16.812 --> 07:18.645
Oh!

07:18.689 --> 07:21.022
This is the first time
I've attempted

07:21.066 --> 07:22.899
a canister weld
like this.

07:22.943 --> 07:28.196
We will find out if Andy Alm
is up to the task.

07:28.240 --> 07:30.407
What the hell did I do
with those files?

07:30.451 --> 07:32.409
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:32.453 --> 07:34.202
- Bladesmiths!

07:34.246 --> 07:36.413
You have only two hours
remaining to finish your work!

07:36.457 --> 07:37.873
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:37.916 --> 07:39.416
- Cool as a cucumber,
this guy.

07:39.460 --> 07:42.169
- Once we get it prepped,
get it welded,

07:42.212 --> 07:43.795
then we can start
making a blade.

07:43.839 --> 07:45.589
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

07:45.632 --> 07:47.883
Fish guts, I hate that
when that happens.

07:47.926 --> 07:50.302
Can you weld 'em
without cleaning 'em off?

07:50.345 --> 07:53.054
Yes, you can, but that's
even a greater risk.

07:53.098 --> 07:55.891
- He's kicking butt and
being cool about it.

07:55.934 --> 07:58.560
That's what I like, you know,
it's experience.

07:58.604 --> 08:00.061
- How's your billet?
It looks really good.

08:00.105 --> 08:01.688
- We'll know when we go
in the oil bath.

08:01.732 --> 08:03.023
- You're the boss, man.

08:03.066 --> 08:05.108
<i> [rock music]</i>

08:05.152 --> 08:07.652
- Now that I've got
the mild steel bit

08:07.696 --> 08:10.780
